[SN]TITLE[SN]
Japanese stocks rise even as yen passes key level against dollar

[SN]FIRST-SENTENCE[SN]
Japan's stocks rose despite the yen falling below the 100 yen per dollar mark for the second time this year.

[SN]RESTBODY[SN]
The yen strengthened to 99.54 per dollar at one point in US trade on Tuesday, before the dollar recovered slightly to 100.54 yen.
The dollar's rebound came after a senior US central bank official indicated borrowing costs could be lifted as early as September.
Japan's benchmark Nikkei 225 index rose 0.9% to 16,745.64.
Meanwhile, Chinese stocks were muted after a long-delayed scheme connecting Shenzhen and Hong Kong's stock exchange was approved.
The CSI 300 index, which tracks the biggest companies in Shanghai and Shenzhen, rose 0,5%, while the  benchmark Shanghai Composite was flat at 3,111,25.
In Hong Kong, the Hang Seng index rose 0.4% to 22,922.21.
Shares of Hong Kong-based carrier Cathay Pacific fell nearly 8% after its announced an 82% fall in first-half profit.
However, a standout performer have been shares of Shanghai Film Company, which surged by the 44% daily limit on their trading debut.
In South Korea the Kospi index slipped 0.3% to 2,040.81, while in Australia the ASX 200 index was flat at 5,535.00.
